## Caso 2 — partição em `int` formato `YYYYMMDD`

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW workspace_db.view_silver_padronizado_cobranca_opc_baixas AS
SELECT
    dt_foto AS p_dt_foto,

    cast(substr(cast(dt_foto as varchar), 1, 6) as integer) AS mes_ref_yyyymm,
    dt_foto AS dt_ref_yyyymmdd,
    cast(
        date_parse(cast(dt_foto as varchar), '%Y%m%d') as date
    ) AS dt_ref_date,
    cast(
        date_parse(cast(dt_foto as varchar), '%Y%m%d') as timestamp
    ) AS ts_ref,

    contrato,
    produto,
    cast(null as varchar) AS cnpj_raiz,
    cast(null as varchar) AS escritorio,
    cast(null as varchar) AS boleto,
    cast(null as decimal(18,2)) AS vl_pago,
    'OPC' AS origem_pagamento,
    cast(null as varchar) AS tp_acordo,

    current_timestamp AS dt_ingestao_modelo,
    'manual_local' AS id_execucao,

    md5(
        concat(
            coalesce(cast(contrato as varchar), ''),
            '|', coalesce(cast(produto as varchar), ''),
            '|', coalesce(cast(dt_foto as varchar), '')
        )
    ) AS hash_chave_negocio,

    md5(
        concat(
            coalesce(cast(contrato as varchar), ''),
            '|', coalesce(cast(produto as varchar), ''),
            '|', coalesce(cast(dt_foto as varchar), '')
        )
    ) AS hash_atributos
FROM workspace_db.opc;
```

Esse padrão também está alinhado ao exemplo do seu material para `vw_opc_base`, onde:

- `dt_foto AS p_dt_foto`
    
- `mes_ref_yyyymm`
    
- `dt_ref_yyyymmdd`  
    aparecem juntos.
    

